# Spring 2026 TDP Error Reporting Research

**Background & MotivationThe TANF Data Portal (TDP) has meaningfully modernized data reporting by replacing more manual submission methods with a faster, easier file upload experience. Since its MVP stage, research participants have reliably described TDP as a major improvement over prior processes, with one from this round of research noting that what used to take days can now happen “pretty much within minutes” and another describing the current drag-and-drop process as “so much better” than the legacy workflows.

The research also suggests that faster submission does not eliminate the complexity of error resolution. While the portal has improved the speed and visibility of file submission feedback, error correction still depends on a mix of system-generated reports, confirmation emails, monthly feedback reports, coding instructions, internal tools and knowledge, and cross-team communication. This research aimed to document those workflows in depth, clarify what information users rely on most and understand where the current reporting experience supports or complicates users’ ability to resolve errors accurately and efficiently.

## Methods & Approach

This research used remote, semi-structured interview sessions with STT users involved in TANF data submission process. Sessions combined contextual inquiry with current-state workflow discussion. We asked participants to describe who is involved in submissions and corrections (if any), what tools and systems they use, how they review and share error report, and what information they rely on to interpret and resolve errors (if any). The synthesis draws on 13 interview sessions and related TDP Office Hours Webinar as an additional data point to understand broader patterns in user questions, pain points and support needs.

## Core Findings & Research Questions Addressed

### RQ1: How do users currently review, interpret, and share error reports to identify and correct data issues?

There is no single, standardized error correction workflow across STTs. Users vary in how and if they review reports, who interprets the errors, where corrections happen and whether corrected files are resubmitted immediately or addressed in a later reporting cycle. With some STTs, one person owns the full process end to end; in others, reports are filtered, summarized, or routed to program staff, field offices, IT teams or vendors for investigation and correction. These workflows differ significantly by team structure, system constraints and internal practices. For a more detailed visual breakdown of several workflow examples, refer to the [Mural Error Report Research Process Maps](https://app.mural.co/t/raft2792/m/raft2792/1775758185116/1dbb7d11b062555b38db6b5f388ad7546553604d). 
#### People find TDP's submission workflow intuitive and timesaving

*“I did experience life before the data portal and it is so much easier to do the drag and drop. I tell everybody we need that for all the programs and all the reports cause it’s great….Before we had the data portal…we \[would\] submit a ticket to the tech team. It was a whole process. It's so much better…To submit the data and now it's like two seconds drag and drop. It's so much better.”* – S11-P1 (Data Analyst)

Across several interviews, participants described the drag-and-drop upload flow, the faster post-submission response, and the general submission experience as easier, more intuitive and better than older SFTP or email-based workflows.

#### While some participants noted errors were easier to interpret than in the legacy system, the interpretation and correction process can still be laborious

*“We have to go into the federal reporting rules and try to figure out, this must be what they mean. It is sometimes **trying to decipher why it's in there, what's not adding up quite right**. If the error messages could be more plain talked, but knowing we have a robust data team in our organization we have the capacity to look at that logic. ie: it's supposed to read this way and it allows us to look at our own coding, etc…”* – S10-P4

Through our research sessions we found that TDP has reduced submission friction more than it has reduced correction friction. The more difficult work still begins after the file is processed. Analysts and program staff must interpret errors, map them back to internal case management & eligibility systems, and coordinate with the right people to see that issues are corrected and new files generated before resubmitting.

#### STT team churn remains disruptive and can result in lost knowledge about core TDP features

*"The lady who was here before us, she passed away and we didn’t have the training when we came. \[S09-P3\] had a really quick…training and she left us some very, very detailed notes. Thank goodness for that…” – S09-P1 (Data Analyst)*

Past research has revealed a wide diversity of experience working with TANF data within TDP users; ranging from 20+ year “veterans” to people brand new to TANF. Interviews with newer staffers in this round of research illustrated a number of potential friction points. One example was a participant group who were unaware of error reports within TDP despite their submissions generating them. We believe this kind of situation may be mitigated by feature improvements like the recent addition of “Action needed” to email notifications relating to available error reports as was ell as the consolidation of Submission History and Current Submission tabs. However, these findings emphasize that we must continue to design for brand new users as well as experienced ones.

Additionally, several participants either did not routinely use the immediate Error Reports in Submission History or were unsure how those reports related to the later Monthly Feedback Reports. This was most visible in S09-01 and S03-P1, where users relied on email or Yun’s follow-up as the trigger to review errors. With S13-P1, the participant knew the immediate report existed but recalled thinking at one point they “weren’t supposed to be using that” because it was not “100% accurate.”

#### Some participants were unaware of expectations for resubmission and noted that while they correct data, they don’t resubmit it

*"I know some states resubmit; we never have"* – S02-P1(Data Analyst)

We encountered multiple states that don’t resubmit their corrected data to TDP. To some, it seemed to be mostly an expectation-gap with participants. Resubmission was viewed as an unnecessary extra step since data would be corrected in their systems and included in future submissions in the form of Active or Closed cases. We believe another factor at play here is a relatively high level of data quality; guaranteeing that those initial submissions fulfil program requirements.

Other participants shared with us that their ability to resubmit is caught up in constraints of their current systems. Particularly where analysts may have limited direct control over file exports because the data is generated through IT teams or vendor-managed scripts. In this instance, their system had been configured to produce data files quarterly and had no option to re-export after an off-cycle correction (S10). We were told that modifications were possible, but as we move towards better communication of program guidance for resubmission we should keep in mind the potential that process changes come hand-in-hand with technology changes that may take extended periods of time for states to implement.

### Average Quantitative Product Ratings (Scale of 1-5)

**Ease of Locating Information on Error Reports: 4.4 / 5This question focused on how easy or difficult it is to find specific data points within the error report. Participants familiar with making corrections generally gave high ratings for the layout of reports. The inclusion of case numbers was a major factor in those ratings for allowing users to immediately identify implicated records in their systems. Many participants noted that a rating of 4 or 5 is only possible because they have memorized the coding instructions and those who were newer to the process without “magic knowledge” the reports would be significantly more difficult to use. S11-P1 noted that while finding items in the report is “very easy” the difficulty lies in “looking up the actual case information in our \[internal\] system.”

**Ease of Locating Information to Make Corrections: 2.75 / 5**
This question focused on how easy or difficult it is to interpret the error and determine the specific steps to fix them. Ratings dropped when asked about the intellectual task of correcting errors. S04-2 rated this a 2.5 because while the data is there, understanding the “why” behind an error often requires “brainstorming” and deep knowledge of the coding instructions/

S11-P1 highlighted that while finding items on the report is “very easy” the actual difficulty lies in looking up the case information.

### RQ2: What information and references do users rely on most when resolving errors (i.e. case number, error type, reporting period, coding instructions, etc.)?We validated that users primarily rely on the columns most suited to looking up coding instructions and relevant case data when interpreting error reports**

*“Where it says item 41 work eligible individual indicator \[the error column\], I will a lot of times look up what that is and then put that little snippet in there… so they don’t have to go look up what those different things are to determine if that was correct or not correct.”* – S11-P1 (Data Analyst)

The information users depend on most is consistently record or case-level and action-oriented: Case number, report month or quarter, and the error message. These fields are a bridge between TDP and their workflows in case management or eligibility systems. Among some county-administered states we spoke to, case numbers play an even bigger role due to being constructed with county identifiers in their later digits which come into play as the state forwards questions or change requests to county staff/case workers. This answers one of the study’s core research questions directly: users are not looking first for broad metadata; they are looking for the fastest path from a flagged case/record to an actionable correction.

#### Some users are taking advantage of the Excel format by applying sorting and filtering to their error reports

***"Then I'll, you know, filter the list and sort it by case number** so I can see all the number, all the errors for each case and then then I'll go research them and see if there's anything that we can do on our end to fix it."* – S08-P1 (Data Analyst)

We saw instances of some participants leaning into the Excel format by applying sorts and filtering to error reports. Sorting by case number, filtering by error type or grouping by custom identifiers in case numbers to aid in distributing portions of reports to different team members or offices. This is also suggestive for how we might move forward toward in-app error report functionality and the interactivity some users will likely be looking for out of it. The fact that error reports today can become more than the sum of their intended functionality in this way also suggests a need to maintain downloadable versions of error reports, at least until in-app versions are more feature rich than they may be at launch.

### RQ3: Does the organization and hierarchy of the error report align with users’ mental models and support efficient scanning and correction?

#### Users primarily care about the Critical tab of error reports with mixed reactions to the Summary tab

*“I checked to see the critical errors, so they know those are the ones that I can actually look up because they give you case numbers… the critical tab is the one that I’m most concerned about and that’s the ones where I spend more time looking up the cases.” – S01-P1*

*“Can you show me the summary tab? Is this new? I swear that our reports that we had looked at before only had one tab. Maybe I’m misremembering. Is critical a subset of the summary?”* – S04-P1

The hierarchy of the report only partially aligns with users’ mental models. The critical tab often aligns well when it exposes specific records that can be worked immediately. The summary tab is more mixed: some users check it to get a sense of the scale of errors in their data, but others report not using it; or not having known it existed. They shared with us that they find the aggregate view of data it contains less actionable for corrections; and therefore less useful (S01-P1)l. In practice, people tend to think in one of two ways: case-first when they are correcting records, or error-type-first when they are diagnosing a systemic issue. The report works best when it supports those two modes clearly.

Some users make certain corrections directly in the submission files in Notepad; often to overcome system-caused errors**

*“Sometimes we make manual edits to the text files. It’s very burdensome to have to do edits because we don’t have a software platform to edit the actual text files, so I’m usually doing it in notepad.”* – S04-P1

A dichotomy we’ve frequently used to better understand the root causes of errors is that of system-caused errors vs. Errors of data entry or data availability.

System-caused errors are the result of improper or outdated data processing as data are converted from a given STT’s source of truth systems into the submission file format. Sometimes they're problems in system logic that have been around for years, and sometimes they’re newly introduced by new vendor software that’s not yet dialed in for a given STT’s systems. They can also emerge when coding instructions are changed and STT systems haven't yet had time to adjust.

Errors or data entry or data availability range from problems like a case worker making a typo when entering data to a given value not yet existing; either because it wasn’t yet provided by the TANF recipient or because it can’t yet be (as is frequently the case for collecting social security numbers for newborns or those at certain staged of the immigration process).

The participants we spoke to who reported using Notepad to enter corrections seemed to be exclusively doing so for the system-caused errors. We heard from multiple participants that while their technical & vendor teams are responsive to fixing these kinds of issues it often takes a timeline of months to a year for a given problem to be addressed. These Notepad corrections are a proactive bridge to make corrections in the interim before systemic improvements are made that eliminate the errors going forward.

### RQ4: Do system cues and guidance (i.e., status indicators, alerts, tooltips, embedded instructions) improve clarity, confidence, and speed of error resolution?

#### Impact of System Cues and Guidance

*"We'd love to have more description of what the errors actually mean rather than being a code speak... that from the programmatic side that would save a lot of time... It is not intuitive."* – S10-P1

System cues and guidance do help, but they help most when they are close to the work. Status messages, confirmation emails, timestamps and embedded links clearly improve confidence. However, users still lean heavily on coding instructions, federal FAQs, printed guides, local notes, bookmarks, contact with Yun and internal tools because many errors are only fully understandable when paired with external context. Today’s experience is functional, but it still asks users to do a great deal of translation work outside the portal.

*“When I submitted, a little line shows up at the top that says submitted successfully... but it doesn't say submitted successfully with errors... The only way I know there's an error is... once I hit that submit successfully button... I am going to log out... we don't know the errors happening until the e-mail comes in."* – S03-P3

Interviews suggested recurring confusion between the immediate Error Reports shown after upload and the Monthly Feedback Reports distributed by Yun via email, also provided in the Monthly Feedback page. Most participants described uploading files, leaving TDP and only returning once the confirmation or feedback email arrives, suggesting these emails provide strong value as both prompts for follow-up action and historical audit documentation. Additionally, the separation between the Submission and History tabs may cause newer users to overlook the upload Error Report entirely. Overall, while the current experience is functional, users still perform significant translation and reconciliation work across multiple tools, communications and external references to fully understand and resolve issues.

## Next Steps: Research and Design Priorities / Make the report ecosystem legible

Knowledge Center usage is mixed. Some participants use it often, bookmark it, or rely on trainings and related resources. Others barely use it, are only vaguely aware of it, or said it rarely answers the question they actually have. S04 was especially direct that the Knowledge Center has almost never been helpful for the specific answers they need, while S13 described heavy use but still said some information can be difficult to find without bookmarking. The lesson is that documentation cannot remain a separate destination if the real interpretive burden occurs inside a correction flow.

## Research and Design Priorities

Our research points to one high-level conclusion: the opportunity is not simply to make error reports *look* cleaner. The bigger opportunity is to have TDP behave more like a collaborative correction system. One that is case-linked, severity-aware, easier to route, easier to explain and better at preserving confidence from first upload through final audit trail. That direction is the one most likely to improve both user efficiency and data quality at the same time.

1.  **Make the report ecosystem legible.** Users need a clearer model of what the immediate submission report does, what the later feedback reports do, how they overlap and what action each one should trigger. That distinction exists today, but it is still opaque enough that at least some users are unsure whether they should rely on one, the other or both together. A future design should name those stages explicitly and make the recommended action model visible.

We plan to investigate avenues of communicating program guidance and expectations more explicitly in-app, including via commentary in a guided app tour experience (Shepherd.js being one tool that we could leverage).

2.  **Make the report default to actionability**. The most useful information should be front-loaded: case number, period, error message, affected field, and contextual cues that help route work. Aggregate summaries should remain available, but they should behave as secondary views for scale, pattern recognition and monitoring rather than the primary place users begin correction. The transcripts strongly suggest that the portal should support both a case-work queue (users typically work through spreadsheet rows, flat files or case lists generated from error reports) and an error-pattern view (scanning for recurring validation issues or repeated error categories to identify systemic problems) with a clear bridge between them. One hypothesis we plan to investigate with future in-app errors research is whether by leaning into more interactive reports that can be sorted, grouped, and filtered in more dynamic ways we might find ways to communicate Summary tab information in a context that’s more directly actionable for users.

3.  **Reduce handoff and error interpretation work & support selective, contextual error sharing.** Teams do not want every downstream partner inside TDP itself and TDP access is also limited to a small number of submitters. Currently counties, program units, local offices and IT teams often receive clipped reports, screenshots, extracted Excel slices, or translated notes rather than direct portal access. Therefore, design should support collaboration without assuming expanded portal seats are the answer. This suggests an opportunity to explore how we might provide a cleaner way distribute specific errors relative to the right people so that they may investigate and relay corrections.

4.  **Explainability and severity.** The interface should do more than say a value failed. It should help users understand what was expected, what was received, which field or rule triggered the issue, and how urgent or structurally significant the issue is from ACF’s perspective. When users can see that context, they can reduce their time manually decoding the report, cross-referencing instructions and reviewing cases just to discover whether they are looking at a one-off error or a system-wide problem.

5.  **Preserve confidence and audit signals.** Emails, timestamps, submission history and transmission-like summaries are not peripheral. They reassure users that the file truly went through, support audit requests and help people reconstruct what happened later. Design work should preserve that reassurance layer, make automated statuses unambiguous and consider whether a downloadable transmission summary or equivalent audit artifact should be easier to access in the current platform.

6.  **More quality work upstream.** Several STTs have already built internal validations, pre-submission scans, quarterly review routines, or defect queries to catch issues before TDP surfaces them. That behavior is a strong signal that the long-term opportunity is larger than better post-submission reports alone. Better pre-submission validation, stronger structured guidance and deeper workflow support would reduce downstream rework, lower cognitive load and improve confidence before the file ever enters the portal.

